# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: climate-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Numerical **climate models** (or **climate system models**, or **earth system models**) are mathematical models that can simulate the interactions of important drivers of climate.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These drivers are the atmosphere, oceans, land surface and ice.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Scientists use climate models to study the dynamics of the climate system and to make projections of future climate and of climate change.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Climate models can also be qualitative (i.e. not numerical) models and contain narratives, largely descriptive, of possible futures.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Climate models take account of incoming energy from the Sun as well as outgoing energy from Earth.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] An imbalance results in a change in temperature.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The incoming energy from the Sun is in the form of short wave electromagnetic radiation, chiefly visible and short-wave (near) infrared.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The outgoing energy is in the form of long wave (far) infrared electromagnetic energy.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These processes are part of the greenhouse effect.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example, a simple radiant heat transfer model treats the Earth as a single point and averages outgoing energy.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This can be expanded vertically (radiative-convective models) and horizontally.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] More complex models are the coupled atmosphere–ocean–sea ice global climate models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These types of models solve the full equations for mass transfer, energy transfer and radiant exchange.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In addition, other types of models can be interlinked.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example Earth System Models include also land use as well as land use changes.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This allows researchers to predict the interactions between climate and ecosystems.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Climate models are systems of differential equations based on the basic laws of physics, fluid motion, and chemistry.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Scientists divide the planet into a 3-dimensional grid and apply the basic equations to those grids.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Atmospheric models calculate winds, heat transfer, radiation, relative humidity, and surface hydrology within each grid and evaluate interactions with neighboring points.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These are coupled with oceanic models to simulate climate variability and change that occurs on different timescales due to shifting ocean currents and the much larger heat storage capacity of the global ocean.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] External drivers of change may also be applied.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Including an ice-sheet model better accounts for long term effects such as sea level rise.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Complex climate models enable extreme event attribution, which is the science of identifying and quantifying the role that human-caused climate change plays in the frequency, intensity and impacts of extreme weather events.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Attribution science aims to determine the degree to which such events can be explained by or linked to human-caused global warming, and are not simply due to random climate variability or natural weather patterns.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Big climate models are essential but they are not perfect.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Attention still needs to be given to the real world (what is happening and why).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The global models are essential to assimilate all the observations, especially from space (satellites) and produce comprehensive analyses of what is happening, and then they can be used to make predictions/projections.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Simple models have a role to play that is widely abused and fails to recognize the simplifications such as not including a water cycle.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] A general circulation model (GCM) is a type of climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] It employs a mathematical model of the general circulation of a planetary atmosphere or ocean.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] It uses the Navier–Stokes equations on a rotating sphere with thermodynamic terms for various energy sources (radiation, latent heat).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These equations are the basis for computer programs used to simulate the Earth's atmosphere or oceans.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Atmospheric and oceanic GCMs (AGCM and OGCM) are key components along with sea ice and land-surface components.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] GCMs and global climate models are used for weather forecasting, understanding the climate, and forecasting climate change.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Atmospheric GCMs (AGCMs) model the atmosphere and impose sea surface temperatures as boundary conditions.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Coupled atmosphere-ocean GCMs (AOGCMs, e.g.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] HadCM3, EdGCM, GFDL CM2.X, ARPEGE-Climat) combine the two models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The first general circulation climate model that combined both oceanic and atmospheric processes was developed in the late 1960s at the NOAA Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory AOGCMs represent the pinnacle of complexity in climate models and internalise as many processes as possible.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] However, they are still under development and uncertainties remain.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] They may be coupled to models of other processes, such as the carbon cycle, so as to better model feedback effects.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Versions designed for decade to century time scale climate applications were created by Syukuro Manabe and Kirk Bryan at the Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory (GFDL) in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These models are based on the integration of a variety of fluid dynamical, chemical and sometimes biological equations.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Simulation of the climate system in full 3-D space and time was impractical prior to the establishment of large computational facilities starting in the 1960s.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In order to begin to understand which factors may have changed Earth's paleoclimate states, the constituent and dimensional complexities of the system needed to be reduced.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] A simple quantitative model that balanced incoming/outgoing energy was first developed for the atmosphere in the late 19th century.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Other EBMs similarly seek an economical description of surface temperatures by applying the conservation of energy constraint to individual columns of the Earth-atmosphere system.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Essential features of EBMs include their relative conceptual simplicity and their ability to sometimes produce analytical solutions.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Some models account for effects of ocean, land, or ice features on the surface budget.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Others include interactions with parts of the water cycle or carbon cycle.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] A variety of these and other reduced system models can be useful for specialized tasks that supplement GCMs, particularly to bridge gaps between simulation and understanding.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Zero-dimensional models consider Earth as a point in space, analogous to the 1990 *Pale Blue Dot* photograph as viewed by *Voyager 1*, or an astronomer's view of very distant objects.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This dimensionless view while highly limited is still useful in that the laws of physics are applicable in a bulk fashion to unknown objects, or in an appropriate lumped manner if some major properties of the object are known.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example, astronomers know that most planets in our own solar system feature some kind of solid/liquid surface surrounded by a gaseous atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This very simple model is quite instructive.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example, it shows the temperature sensitivity to changes in the solar constant, Earth albedo, or effective Earth emissivity.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The effective emissivity also gauges the strength of the atmospheric greenhouse effect, since it is the ratio of the thermal emissions escaping to space versus those emanating from the surface.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The calculated emissivity can be compared to available data.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Terrestrial surface emissivities are all in the range of 0.96 to 0.99 (except for some small desert areas which may be as low as 0.7).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Clouds, however, which cover about half of the planet's surface, have an average emissivity of about 0.5 (which must be reduced by the fourth power of the ratio of cloud absolute temperature to average surface absolute temperature) and an average cloud temperature of about 258 K (−15 °C; 5 °F).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Taking all this properly into account results in an effective earth emissivity of about 0.64 (earth average temperature 285 K (12 °C; 53 °F)).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Dimensionless models have also been constructed with functionally distinct atmospheric layers from the surface.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The simplest of these is the zero-dimensional, one-layer model, which may be readily extended to an arbitrary number of atmospheric layers.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The surface and atmospheric layer(s) are each characterized by a corresponding temperature and emissivity value, but no thickness.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Applying radiative equilibrium (i.e conservation of energy) at the idealized interfaces between layers produces a set of coupled equations which are solvable.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] These multi-layered EBMs are examples of multi-compartment models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] They can estimate average temperatures closer to those observed for Earth's surface and troposphere.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] They likewise further illustrate the radiative heat transfer processes which underlie the greenhouse effect.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Quantification of this phenomenon using a version of the one-layer model was first published by Svante Arrhenius in year 1896.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Water vapor is a main determinant of the emissivity of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] It both influences the flows of radiation and is influenced by convective flows of heat in a manner that is consistent with its equilibrium concentration and temperature as a function of elevation (i.e. relative humidity distribution).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Radiative-convective models typically use a distributed model of the atmosphere versus elevation.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This has advantages over the lumped models and also lays a foundation for more complex models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] They can estimate both surface temperature and the temperature variation with elevation in a more realistic manner.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In particular, they properly simulate the observed decline in upper atmospheric temperature and the rise in surface temperature when trace amounts of other non-condensible greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide are included.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Other parameters are sometimes included to simulate localized effects in other dimensions and to address the factors that move energy about Earth.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example, the effect of ice-albedo feedback on global climate sensitivity has been investigated using a one-dimensional radiative-convective climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The zero-dimensional model may be expanded to consider the energy transported horizontally in the atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This kind of model may well be zonally averaged.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This model has the advantage of allowing a rational dependence of *local* albedo and emissivity on temperature – the poles can be allowed to be icy and the equator warm – but the lack of true dynamics means that horizontal transports have to be specified.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Early examples include research of Mikhail Budyko and William D.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Sellers who worked on the *Budyko-Sellers model*.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This work also showed the role of positive feedback in the climate system and has been considered foundational for the energy balance models since its publication in 1969.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Depending on the nature of questions asked and the pertinent time scales, there are, on the one extreme, conceptual, more inductive models, and, on the other extreme, general circulation models operating at the highest spatial and temporal resolution currently feasible.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Models of intermediate complexity bridge the gap.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Its atmosphere is a 2.5-dimensional statistical-dynamical model with 7.5° × 22.5° resolution and time step of half a day; the ocean is MOM-3 (Modular Ocean Model) with a 3.75° × 3.75° grid and 24 vertical levels.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Box models are simplified versions of complex systems, reducing them to boxes linked by fluxes.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The boxes contain reservoirs (i.e. inventories) of species of matter and energy that are assumed to be mixed homogeneously.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The concentration of any species is therefore uniform at any time within a box.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] However, the abundance of a species within a given box may vary as a function of time due to input flows or output flows; and may also vary due to the production, consumption or transformation of a species within the box.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Simple box models, i.e. box model with a small number of boxes whose properties (e.g. their volume) do not change with time, are often useful to derive analytical formulas describing the dynamical and steady-state abundances of a species.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The formulae are called governing equations and are derived from conservation laws (e.g. conservation of energy, conservation of mass, etc.).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Larger sets of interacting species and equations are evaluated with numerical techniques to describe behavior of the system.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Box models are used extensively to simulate environmental systems and ecosystems.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In 1961 Henry Stommel was the first to use a simple 2-box model to study the stability of large-scale ocean circulation.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] A more complex model has examined interactions between ocean circulation and the carbon cycle.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The field of complex networks has emerged as an important area of science to generate novel insights into nature of complex systems The application of network theory to climate science is a young and emerging field.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] To identify and analyze patterns in global climate, scientists model climate data as complex networks.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Unlike most real-world networks where nodes and edges are well defined, in climate networks, nodes are identified as the sites in a spatial grid of the underlying global climate data set, which can be represented at various resolutions.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Two nodes are connected by an edge depending on the degree of statistical similarity (that may be related to dependence) between the corresponding pairs of time-series taken from climate records.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The climate network approach enables novel insights into the dynamics of the climate system over different spatial and temporal scales.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In 1956, Norman Phillips developed a mathematical model that realistically depicted monthly and seasonal patterns in the troposphere.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This was the first successful climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Several groups then began working to create general circulation models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The first general circulation climate model combined oceanic and atmospheric processes and was developed in the late 1960s at the Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory, a component of the U.S.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] By 1975, Manabe and Wetherald had developed a three-dimensional global climate model that gave a roughly accurate representation of the current climate.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Doubling CO2 in the model's atmosphere gave a roughly 2 °C rise in global temperature.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Several other kinds of computer models gave similar results: it was impossible to make a model that gave something resembling the actual climate and not have the temperature rise when the CO2 concentration was increased.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] National Center for Atmospheric Research had developed the Community Atmosphere Model (CAM), which can be run by itself or as the atmospheric component of the Community Climate System Model.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The latest update (version 3.1) of the standalone CAM was issued on 1 February 2006.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] In 1986, efforts began to initialize and model soil and vegetation types, resulting in more realistic forecasts.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Coupled ocean-atmosphere climate models, such as the Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research's HadCM3 model, are being used as inputs for climate change studies.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Meta-analyses of past climate change models show that they have generally been accurate, albeit conservative, under-predicting levels of warming.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The Coupled Model Intercomparison Project (CMIP) has been a leading effort to foster improvements in GCMs and climate change understanding since 1995.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] The World Climate Research Programme (WCRP), hosted by the World Meteorological Organization (WMO), coordinates research activities on climate modelling worldwide.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] National Research Council report discussed how the large and diverse U.S. climate modeling enterprise could evolve to become more unified.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Efficiencies could be gained by developing a common software infrastructure shared by all U.S. climate researchers, and holding an annual climate modeling forum, the report found.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Cloud-resolving climate models are nowadays run on high intensity super-computers which have a high power consumption and thus cause CO2 emissions.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] They require exascale computing (billion billion – i.e., a quintillion – calculations per second).
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] For example, the Frontier exascale supercomputer consumes 29 MW.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] It can simulate a year’s worth of climate at cloud resolving scales in a day.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Parametrization (or parameterization) in an atmospheric model (either weather model or climate model) is a method of replacing processes that are too small-scale or complex to be physically represented in the model by a simplified process.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] This can be contrasted with other processes—e.g., large-scale flow of the atmosphere—that are explicitly resolved within the models.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Associated with these parametrizations are various *parameters* used in the simplified processes.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Examples include the descent rate of raindrops, convective clouds, simplifications of the atmospheric radiative transfer on the basis of atmospheric radiative transfer codes, and cloud microphysics.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Radiative parametrizations are important to both atmospheric and oceanic modeling alike.
[src:climate-modeling/climate-model] Atmospheric emissions from different sources within individual grid boxes also need to be parametrized to determine their impact on air quality.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] In climatology, the **Coupled Model Intercomparison Project** (CMIP) is a collaborative framework designed to improve knowledge of climate change.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] It was organized in 1995 by the Working Group on Coupled Modelling (WGCM) of the World Climate Research Programme (WCRP).
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] It is developed in phases to foster the climate model improvements but also to support national and international assessments of climate change.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] A related project is the Atmospheric Model Intercomparison Project (AMIP) for global coupled ocean-atmosphere general circulation models (GCMs).
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] Coupled models are computer-based models of the Earth's climate, in which models of different subsystems (such as the atmosphere, oceans, land, ice) are "coupled" together, and interact in simulations.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison (PCMDI) at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory has been supporting the several CMIP phases by helping WGCM to determine the scope of the project, by maintaining the project's data base and by participating in data analysis.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] CMIP has received model output from the pre-industrial climate simulations ("control runs") and 1% per year increasing-CO2 simulations of about 30 coupled GCMs.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] including 20th Century Climate in Coupled Models (20C3M), include more realistic scenarios of climate forcing for both historical, paleoclimate and future scenarios.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The response to the CMIP1 announcement was very successful and up to 18 global coupled models participated in the data collection representing most of the international groups with global coupled GCMs.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] In consequence, at the September 1996 meeting of the CLIVAR NEG2 numerical experimentation group in Victoria, Canada, it was decided that CMIP2 will be an inter-comparison of 1% per year compound CO2 increase integrations (80 years in length) where CO2 doubles at around year 70.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] During 2005 and 2006, a collection of climate model outputs was coordinated and stored by PCMDI.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The climate model outputs included simulations of past, present and future climate scenarios.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] This activity enabled those climate models, outside the major modeling centers to perform research of relevance to climate scientists preparing the IPCC Fourth Assessment Report (IPCC-AR4).
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] For the CMIP3 a list of 20 different experiments were proposed, and the PCMDI kept the documentation of all the global climate model involved.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] Additional information and data-sets are in.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The next phase of the project (2010–2014) was CMIP5.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] CMIP5 included more metadata describing model simulations than previous phases.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The METAFOR project created an exhaustive schema describing the scientific, technical, and numerical aspects of CMIP runs which was archived along with the output data.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] A main objective of the CMIP5 experiments was to address outstanding scientific questions that arose as part of the IPCC AR4 process, improve understanding of climate, and to provide estimates of future climate change that will be useful to those considering its possible consequences.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The IPCC Fifth Assessment Report summarizes information of CMIP5 experiments, while the CMIP5 experimental protocol was endorsed by the 12th Session of the WCRP Working on this Group on Coupled Modelling (WGCM).
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] Planning meetings for Phase 6 began in 2013, and an overview of the design and organization was published in 2016.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] By 2018 CMIP6 had endorsed 23 Model Intercomparison Projects (MIPs) involving 33 modeling groups in 16 countries.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] A small number of common experiments were also planned.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] The deadline for submission of papers to contribute to the IPCC 6th Assessment Report Working Group I is early 2020.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] However, CMIP-Endorsed Model Intercomparison Projects (MIPs) are still built on the DECK and CMIP historical simulations, therefore their main goal is just to address a wider range of specific questions.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] This structure will be kept in future CMIP experiments.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] CMIP6 also aims to be consistent regarding common standards and documentation.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] To achieve that it includes methods to facilitate a wider distribution and characterization of model outputs, and common standard tools for their analyses.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] A number of guides has been created for data managers, modelers and users.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] A set of official/common forcings datasets are available for the studies under DECK, as well as several MIPS.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] That allows for more sensible comparisons on the model ensemble created under the CMIP6 umbrella.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] These **common dataset forcings** are stored and coordinated by input4MIPS (input datasets for Model Intercomparison Projects).
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] Beyond these historical forcings, CMIP6 also has a common set of future scenarios comprising land use and emissions as required for the future Shared Socioeconomic Pathways (SSPs) which have replaced the Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) from prior models.
[src:climate-modeling/coupled-model-intercomparison-project] For CMIP7 a more continuous release approach than in previous phases was announced: In addition to DECK releases and a growing number of community MIPS, so-called fast track experiments supporting specific requirements will be released.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] A **general circulation model** (**GCM**) is a type of climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The acronym *GCM* originally stood for *General Circulation Model*.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Recently, a second meaning came into use, namely *Global Climate Model*.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] While these do not refer to the same thing, General Circulation Models are typically the tools used for modeling climate, and hence the two terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, the term "global climate model" is ambiguous and may refer to an integrated framework that incorporates multiple components including a general circulation model, or may refer to the general class of climate models that use a variety of means to represent the climate mathematically.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Atmospheric (AGCMs) and oceanic GCMs (OGCMs) can be coupled to form an atmosphere-ocean coupled general circulation model (CGCM or AOGCM).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] With the addition of submodels such as a sea ice model or a model for evapotranspiration over land, AOGCMs become the basis for a full climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] General Circulation Models (GCMs) discretise the equations for fluid motion and energy transfer and integrate these over time.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Unlike simpler models, GCMs divide the atmosphere and/or oceans into grids of discrete "cells", which represent computational units.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Unlike simpler models which make mixing assumptions, processes internal to a cell—such as convection—that occur on scales too small to be resolved directly are parameterised at the cell level, while other functions govern the interface between cells.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Three-dimensional (more properly four-dimensional) GCMs apply discrete equations for fluid motion and integrate these forward in time.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They contain parameterisations for processes such as convection that occur on scales too small to be resolved directly.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] A simple general circulation model (SGCM) consists of a dynamic core that relates properties such as temperature to others such as pressure and velocity.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Examples are programs that solve the primitive equations, given energy input and energy dissipation in the form of scale-dependent friction, so that atmospheric waves with the highest wavenumbers are most attenuated.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Such models may be used to study atmospheric processes, but are not suitable for climate projections.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Atmospheric GCMs (AGCMs) model the atmosphere (and typically contain a land-surface model as well) using imposed sea surface temperatures (SSTs).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] A GCM contains prognostic equations that are a function of time (typically winds, temperature, moisture, and surface pressure) together with diagnostic equations that are evaluated from them for a specific time period.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] As an example, pressure at any height can be diagnosed by applying the hydrostatic equation to the predicted surface pressure and the predicted values of temperature between the surface and the height of interest.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Pressure is used to compute the pressure gradient force in the time-dependent equation for the winds.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] OGCMs model the ocean (with fluxes from the atmosphere imposed) and may contain a sea ice model.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] For example, the standard resolution of HadOM3 is 1.25 degrees in latitude and longitude, with 20 vertical levels, leading to approximately 1,500,000 variables.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] HadCM3, GFDL CM2.X) combine the two submodels.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They remove the need to specify fluxes across the interface of the ocean surface.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] These models are the basis for model predictions of future climate, such as are discussed by the IPCC.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] AOGCMs internalise as many processes as possible.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They have been used to provide predictions at a regional scale.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] While the simpler models are generally susceptible to analysis and their results are easier to understand, AOGCMs may be nearly as hard to analyse as the climate itself.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The fluid equations for AGCMs are made discrete using either the finite difference method or the spectral method.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] For finite differences, a grid is imposed on the atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The simplest grid uses constant angular grid spacing (i.e., a latitude/longitude grid).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, non-rectangular grids (e.g., icosahedral) and grids of variable resolution are more often used.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The LMDz model can be arranged to give high resolution over any given section of the planet.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] HadGEM1 (and other ocean models) use an ocean grid with higher resolution in the tropics to help resolve processes believed to be important for the El Niño Southern Oscillation (ENSO).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Spectral models generally use a Gaussian grid, because of the mathematics of transformation between spectral and grid-point space.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Typical AGCM resolutions are between 1 and 5 degrees in latitude or longitude: HadCM3, for example, uses 3.75 in longitude and 2.5 degrees in latitude, giving a grid of 96 by 73 points (96 x 72 for some variables); and has 19 vertical levels.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] This results in approximately 500,000 "basic" variables, since each grid point has four variables (*u*,*v*, *T*, *Q*), though a full count would give more (clouds; soil levels).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] HadGEM1 uses a grid of 1.875 degrees in longitude and 1.25 in latitude in the atmosphere; HiGEM, a high-resolution variant, uses 1.25 x 0.83 degrees respectively.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] These resolutions are lower than is typically used for weather forecasting.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Ocean resolutions tend to be higher, for example, HadCM3 has 6 ocean grid points per atmospheric grid point in the horizontal.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] For a standard finite difference model, uniform gridlines converge towards the poles.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] This would lead to computational instabilities (see CFL condition) and so the model variables must be filtered along lines of latitude close to the poles.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Ocean models suffer from this problem too, unless a rotated grid is used in which the North Pole is shifted onto a nearby landmass.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Spectral models do not suffer from this problem.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Some experiments use geodesic grids and icosahedral grids, which (being more uniform) do not have pole-problems.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Another approach to solving the grid spacing problem is to deform a Cartesian cube such that it covers the surface of a sphere.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Some early versions of AOGCMs required an *ad hoc* process of "flux correction" to achieve a stable climate.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] This resulted from separately prepared ocean and atmospheric models that each used an implicit flux from the other component different than that component could produce.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Such a model failed to match observations.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, if the fluxes were 'corrected', the factors that led to these unrealistic fluxes might be unrecognised, which could affect model sensitivity.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] As a result, the vast majority of models used in the current round of IPCC reports do not use them.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The model improvements that now make flux corrections unnecessary include improved ocean physics, improved resolution in both atmosphere and ocean, and more physically consistent coupling between the atmosphere and ocean submodels.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Improved models now maintain stable, multi-century simulations of surface climate that are considered to be of sufficient quality to allow their use for climate projections.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Moist convection releases latent heat and is important to the Earth's energy budget.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Convection occurs on too small a scale to be resolved by climate models, and hence it must be handled via parameters.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Akio Arakawa did much of the early work, and variants of his scheme are still used, although a variety of different schemes are now in use.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Clouds are also typically handled with a parameter, for a similar lack of scale.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Limited understanding of clouds has limited the success of this strategy, but not due to some inherent shortcomings of the method.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Most models include software to diagnose a wide range of variables for comparison with observations or study of atmospheric processes.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] An example is the 2-metre temperature, which is the standard height for near-surface observations of air temperature.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] This temperature is not directly predicted from the model but is deduced from surface and lowest-model-layer temperatures.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Other software is used for creating plots and animations.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Coupled AOGCMs use transient climate simulations to project/predict climate changes under various scenarios.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] These can be idealised scenarios (most commonly, CO2 emissions increasing at 1%/yr) or based on recent history (usually the "IS92a" or more recently the SRES scenarios).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Which scenarios are most realistic remains uncertain.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The 2001 IPCC Third Assessment Report Figure 9.3 shows the global mean response of 19 different coupled models to an idealised experiment in which emissions increased at 1% per year.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Figure 9.5 shows the response of a smaller number of models to more recent trends.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] For the 7 climate models shown there, the temperature change to 2100 varies from 2 to 4.5 °C with a median of about 3 °C.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Future scenarios do not include unknown events – for example, volcanic eruptions or changes in solar forcing.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] These effects are believed to be small in comparison to greenhouse gas (GHG) forcing in the long term, but large volcanic eruptions, for example, can exert a substantial temporary cooling effect.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Human GHG emissions are a model input, although it is possible to include an economic/technological submodel to provide these as well.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Atmospheric GHG levels are usually supplied as an input, though it is possible to include a carbon cycle model that reflects vegetation and oceanic processes to calculate such levels.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] For the six SRES marker scenarios, IPCC (2007:7–8) gave a "best estimate" of global mean temperature increase (2090–2099 relative to the period 1980–1999) of 1.8 °C to 4.0 °C.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Over the same time period, the "likely" range (greater than 66% probability, based on expert judgement) for these scenarios was for a global mean temperature increase of 1.1 to 6.4 °C.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In 2008 a study made climate projections using several emission scenarios.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In a scenario where global emissions start to decrease by 2010 and then decline at a sustained rate of 3% per year, the likely global average temperature increase was predicted to be 1.7 °C above pre-industrial levels by 2050, rising to around 2 °C by 2100.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In a projection designed to simulate a future where no efforts are made to reduce global emissions, the likely rise in global average temperature was predicted to be 5.5 °C by 2100.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] A rise as high as 7 °C was thought possible, although less likely.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Another no-reduction scenario resulted in a median warming over land (2090–99 relative to the period 1980–99) of 5.1 °C.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Under the same emissions scenario but with a different model, the predicted median warming was 4.1 °C.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] AOGCMs internalise as many processes as are sufficiently understood.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, they are still under development and significant uncertainties remain.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They may be coupled to models of other processes in Earth system models, such as the carbon cycle, so as to better model feedback.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Most recent simulations show "plausible" agreement with the measured temperature anomalies over the past 150 years, when driven by observed changes in greenhouse gases and aerosols.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Agreement improves by including both natural and anthropogenic forcings.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Imperfect models may nevertheless produce useful results.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] GCMs are capable of reproducing the general features of the observed global temperature over the past century.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] A debate over how to reconcile climate model predictions that upper air (tropospheric) warming should be greater than observed surface warming, some of which appeared to show otherwise, was resolved in favour of the models, following data revisions.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Cloud effects are a significant area of uncertainty in climate models.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Clouds have competing effects on climate.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They cool the surface by reflecting sunlight into space; they warm it by increasing the amount of infrared radiation transmitted from the atmosphere to the surface.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In the 2001 IPCC report possible changes in cloud cover were highlighted as a major uncertainty in predicting climate.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Climate researchers around the world use climate models to understand the climate system.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Thousands of papers have been published about model-based studies.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Part of this research is to improve the models.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In 2000, a comparison between measurements and dozens of GCM simulations of ENSO-driven tropical precipitation, water vapor, temperature, and outgoing longwave radiation found similarity between measurements and simulation of most factors.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, the simulated change in precipitation was about one-fourth less than what was observed.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Errors in simulated precipitation imply errors in other processes, such as errors in the evaporation rate that provides moisture to create precipitation.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The other possibility is that the satellite-based measurements are in error.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Either indicates progress is required in order to monitor and predict such changes.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The precise magnitude of future changes in climate is still uncertain; for the end of the 21st century (2071 to 2100), for SRES scenario A2, the change of global average SAT change from AOGCMs compared with 1961 to 1990 is +3.0 °C (5.4 °F) and the range is +1.3 to +4.5 °C (+2.3 to 8.1 °F).
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The IPCC's Fifth Assessment Report asserted "very high confidence that models reproduce the general features of the global-scale annual mean surface temperature increase over the historical period".
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, the report also observed that the rate of warming over the period 1998–2012 was lower than that predicted by 111 out of 114 Coupled Model Intercomparison Project climate models.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The global climate models used for climate projections are similar in structure to (and often share computer code with) numerical models for weather prediction, but are nonetheless logically distinct.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Most weather forecasting is done on the basis of interpreting numerical model results.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Since forecasts are typically a few days or a week and sea surface temperatures change relatively slowly, such models do not usually contain an ocean model but rely on imposed SSTs.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They also require accurate initial conditions to begin the forecast – typically these are taken from the output of a previous forecast, blended with observations.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Weather predictions are required at higher temporal resolutions than climate projections, often sub-hourly compared to monthly or yearly averages for climate.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] However, because weather forecasts only cover around 10 days the models can also be run at higher vertical and horizontal resolutions than climate mode.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Currently the ECMWF runs at 9 km (5.6 mi) resolution as opposed to the 100-to-200 km (62-to-124 mi) scale used by typical climate model runs.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Often local models are run using global model results for boundary conditions, to achieve higher local resolution: for example, the Met Office runs a mesoscale model with an 11 km (6.8 mi) resolution covering the UK, and various agencies in the US employ models such as the NGM and NAM models.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Like most global numerical weather prediction models such as the GFS, global climate models are often spectral models instead of grid models.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Spectral models are often used for global models because some computations in modeling can be performed faster, thus reducing run times.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Climate models use quantitative methods to simulate the interactions of the atmosphere, oceans, land surface and ice.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] All climate models take account of incoming energy as short wave electromagnetic radiation, chiefly visible and short-wave (near) infrared, as well as outgoing energy as long wave (far) infrared electromagnetic radiation from the earth.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Any imbalance results in a change in temperature.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The most talked-about models of recent years relate temperature to emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] These models project an upward trend in the surface temperature record, as well as a more rapid increase in temperature at higher altitudes.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Three (or more properly, four since time is also considered) dimensional GCM's discretise the equations for fluid motion and energy transfer and integrate these over time.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] They also contain parametrisations for processes such as convection that occur on scales too small to be resolved directly.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Other submodels can be interlinked, such as land use, allowing researchers to predict the interaction between climate and ecosystems.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The Climber-3 model uses a 2.5-dimensional statistical-dynamical model with 7.5° × 22.5° resolution and time step of 1/2 a day.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] An oceanic submodel is MOM-3 (Modular Ocean Model) with a 3.75° × 3.75° grid and 24 vertical levels.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] One-dimensional, radiative-convective models were used to verify basic climate assumptions in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] GCMs can form part of Earth system models, e.g. by coupling ice sheet models for the dynamics of the Greenland and Antarctic ice sheets, and one or more chemical transport models (CTMs) for species important to climate.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Thus a carbon chemistry transport model may allow a GCM to better predict anthropogenic changes in carbon dioxide concentrations.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In addition, this approach allows accounting for inter-system feedback: e.g. chemistry-climate models allow the effects of climate change on the ozone hole to be studied.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In 1956, Norman Phillips developed a mathematical model that could realistically depict monthly and seasonal patterns in the troposphere.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] It became the first successful climate model.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Following Phillips's work, several groups began working to create GCMs.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The first to combine both oceanic and atmospheric processes was developed in the late 1960s at the NOAA Geophysical Fluid Dynamics Laboratory.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] By the early 1980s, the United States' National Center for Atmospheric Research had developed the Community Atmosphere Model; this model has been continuously refined.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] In 1996, efforts began to model soil and vegetation types.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Later the Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction and Research's HadCM3 model coupled ocean-atmosphere elements.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] The role of gravity waves was added in the mid-1980s.
[src:climate-modeling/general-circulation-model] Gravity waves are required to simulate regional and global scale circulations accurately.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Weather and climate model gridboxes have sides of between 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) and 300 kilometres (190 mi).
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] A typical cumulus cloud has a scale of less than 1 kilometre (0.62 mi), and would require a grid even finer than this to be represented physically by the equations of fluid motion.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Therefore, the processes that such clouds represent are *parametrized*, by processes of various sophistication.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] In the earliest models, if a column of air in a model gridbox was unstable (i.e., the bottom warmer than the top) then it would be overturned, and the air in that vertical column mixed.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] More sophisticated schemes add enhancements, recognizing that only some portions of the box might convect and that entrainment and other processes occur.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Weather models that have gridboxes with sides between 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) and 25 kilometres (16 mi) can explicitly represent convective clouds, although they still need to parametrize cloud microphysics.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The formation of large-scale (stratus-type) clouds is more physically based: they form when the relative humidity reaches some prescribed value.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Still, sub grid scale processes need to be taken into account.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Rather than assuming that clouds form at 100% relative humidity, the cloud fraction can be related to a critical relative humidity of 70% for stratus-type clouds, and at or above 80% for cumuliform clouds, reflecting the sub grid scale variation that would occur in the real world.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Portions of the precipitation parametrization include the condensation rate, energy exchanges dealing with the change of state from water vapor into liquid drops, and the microphysical component which controls the rate of change from water vapor to water droplets.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The amount of solar radiation reaching ground level in rugged terrain, or due to variable cloudiness, is parametrized as this process occurs on the molecular scale.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] This method of parametrization is also done for the surface flux of energy between the ocean and the atmosphere in order to determine realistic sea surface temperatures and type of sea ice found near the ocean's surface.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Also, the grid size of the models is large when compared to the actual size and roughness of clouds and topography.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Sun angle as well as the impact of multiple cloud layers is taken into account.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Soil type, vegetation type, and soil moisture all determine how much radiation goes into warming and how much moisture is drawn up into the adjacent atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Thus, they are important to parametrize.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Air quality forecasting attempts to predict when the concentrations of pollutants will attain levels that are hazardous to public health.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The concentration of pollutants in the atmosphere is determined by transport, diffusion, chemical transformation, and ground deposition.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Alongside pollutant source and terrain information, these models require data about the state of the fluid flow in the atmosphere to determine its transport and diffusion.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Within air quality models, parametrizations take into account atmospheric emissions from multiple relatively tiny sources (e.g. roads, fields, factories) within specific grid boxes.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The ocean (and, although more variably, the atmosphere) is stratified through density.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] At rest, surfaces of constant density (known as isopycnals in the ocean) will be parallel to surfaces of constant pressure (isobars).
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] However, various processes such as geostrophy and upwelling can result in isopycnals becoming tilted relative to isobars.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] These tilted density surfaces represent a source of potential energy and, if the slope becomes steep enough, a fluid instability known as baroclinic instability can be triggered.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Eddies are generated through baroclinic instability, which act to flatten density surfaces through the slantwise exchange of fluid.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The resulting eddies are formed at a characteristic scale called the Rossby deformation radius.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] This scale depends on the strength of stratification and the coriolis parameter (which in turn depends on the latitude).
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] As a result, baroclinic eddies form on scales of around 1° (~100 km) at the tropics, but less than 1/12° (~10 km) at the poles and in some shelf seas.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Most climate models, such as those run as part of CMIP experiments, are run at a resolution of 1-1/4° in the ocean, and can therefore not resolve baroclinic eddies across large parts of the ocean, particularly at the poles.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] However, high-latitude baroclinic eddies are important for many ocean processes such as the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC), which affects global climate.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] As a result, the effects of eddies are parametrized in climate models, such as through the widely-used Gent-McWilliams (GM) parametrization which represents the isopycnal-flattening effects of eddies as advection (often misinterpreted as diffusion of surfaces).
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] This parametrization is not perfect - for instance, it may overpredict the sensitivity of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current and AMOC to the strength of winds over the Southern Ocean.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] As a result, alternative parametrizations are being developed to improve the representation of eddies in ocean models.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] As model resolution increases, errors associated with moist convective processes are increased as assumptions which are statistically valid for larger grid boxes become questionable once the grid boxes shrink in scale towards the size of the convection itself.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] At resolutions greater than T639, which has a grid box dimension of about 30 kilometres (19 mi), the Arakawa-Schubert convective scheme produces minimal convective precipitation, making most precipitation unrealistically stratiform in nature.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] When a physical process is parametrized, two choices have to be made: what is the structural form (for instance, two variables can be related linearly) and what is the exact value of the parameters (for instance, the constant of proportionality).
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The process of determining the exact values of the parameters in a parametrization is called calibration, or sometimes less precise, tuning.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] Calibration is a difficult process, and different strategies are used to do it.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] One popular method is to run a model, or a submodel, and compare it to a small set of selected metrics, such as temperature.
[src:climate-modeling/parametrization-atmospheric-modeling] The parameters that lead to the model run which resembles reality best are chosen.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The **primitive equations** are a set of nonlinear partial differential equations that are used to approximate global atmospheric flow and are used in most atmospheric models.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The primitive equations may be linearized to yield Laplace's tidal equations, an eigenvalue problem from which the analytical solution to the latitudinal structure of the flow may be determined.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] In general, nearly all forms of the primitive equations relate the five variables *u*, *v*, ω, *T*, *W*, and their evolution over space and time.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The equations were first written down by Vilhelm Bjerknes.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Forces that cause atmospheric motion include the pressure gradient force, gravity, and viscous friction.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Together, they create the forces that accelerate our atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The pressure gradient force causes an acceleration forcing air from regions of high pressure to regions of low pressure.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The gravitational force accelerates objects at approximately 9.8 m/s2 directly towards the center of the Earth.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Using Newton's second law, these forces (referenced in the equations above as the accelerations due to these forces) may be summed to produce an equation of motion that describes this system.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] where n is the number density in mol, and T:=RT is the temperature equivalent value in Joule/mol.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The precise form of the primitive equations depends on the vertical coordinate system chosen, such as pressure coordinates, log pressure coordinates, or sigma coordinates.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Furthermore, the velocity, temperature, and geopotential variables may be decomposed into mean and perturbation components using Reynolds decomposition.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] In this form pressure is selected as the vertical coordinate and the horizontal coordinates are written for the Cartesian tangential plane (i.e. a plane tangent to some point on the surface of the Earth).
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] This form does not take the curvature of the Earth into account, but is useful for visualizing some of the physical processes involved in formulating the equations due to its relative simplicity.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Note that the capital D time derivatives are material derivatives.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Five equations in five unknowns comprise the system.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] When a statement of the conservation of water vapor substance is included, these six equations can form the basis for a numerical weather prediction scheme.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] According to the *National Weather Service Handbook No.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The first term is equal to the change in temperature due to incoming solar radiation and outgoing longwave radiation, which changes with time throughout the day.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The second, third, and fourth terms are due to advection.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Additionally, the variable *T* with subscript is the change in temperature on that plane.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Each *T* is actually different and related to its respective plane.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] This is divided by the distance between grid points to get the change in temperature with the change in distance.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] When multiplied by the wind velocity on that plane, the units kelvins per meter and meters per second give kelvins per second.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The sum of all the changes in temperature due to motions in the *x*, *y*, and *z* directions give the total change in temperature with time.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] This equation and notation works in much the same way as the temperature equation.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] This equation describes the motion of water from one place to another at a point without taking into account water that changes form.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Inside a given system, the total change in water with time is zero.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] However, concentrations are allowed to move with the wind.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] These simplifications make it much easier to understand what is happening in the model.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Things like the temperature (potential temperature), precipitable water, and to an extent the pressure thickness simply move from one spot on the grid to another with the wind.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The wind is forecast slightly differently.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] It uses geopotential, specific heat, the Exner function *π*, and change in sigma coordinate.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The analytic solution to the linearized primitive equations involves a sinusoidal oscillation in time and longitude, modulated by coefficients related to height and latitude.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] where *s* and $\sigma$ are the zonal wavenumber and angular frequency, respectively.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] The solution represents atmospheric waves and tides.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] When the coefficients are separated into their height and latitude components, the height dependence takes the form of propagating or evanescent waves (depending on conditions), while the latitude dependence is given by the Hough functions.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] This analytic solution is only possible when the primitive equations are linearized and simplified.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] Unfortunately many of these simplifications (i.e. no dissipation, isothermal atmosphere) do not correspond to conditions in the actual atmosphere.
[src:climate-modeling/primitive-equations] As a result, a numerical solution which takes these factors into account is often calculated using general circulation models and climate models.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The fundamental quantity that describes a field of radiation is called **spectral radiance** in radiometric terms (in other fields it is often called **specific intensity**).
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] For a very small area element in the radiation field, there can be electromagnetic radiation passing in both senses in every spatial direction through it.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] where $\theta$ is the angle that the unit direction vector ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ makes with a normal to the area element.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The units of the spectral radiance are seen to be energy/time/area/solid angle/frequency.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] In MKS units this would be W·m−2·sr−1·Hz−1 (watts per square-metre-steradian-hertz).
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The equation of radiative transfer simply says that as a beam of radiation travels, it loses energy to absorption, gains energy by emission processes, and redistributes energy by scattering.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Solutions to the equation of radiative transfer form an enormous body of work.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The differences however, are essentially due to the various forms for the emission and absorption coefficients.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] A particularly useful simplification of the equation of radiative transfer occurs under the conditions of local thermodynamic equilibrium (LTE).
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Local equilibrium may apply only to a certain subset of particles in the system.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] For example, LTE is usually applied only to massive particles.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] In a radiating gas, the photons being emitted and absorbed by the gas do not need to be in a thermodynamic equilibrium with each other or with the massive particles of the gas in order for LTE to exist.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] In this situation, the absorbing/emitting medium consists of massive particles which are locally in equilibrium with each other, and therefore have a definable temperature (Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics).
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The radiation field is not, however in equilibrium and is being entirely driven by the presence of the massive particles.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] where $B_{\nu }(T)$ is the black body spectral radiance at temperature T.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Knowing the temperature profile and the density profile of the medium is sufficient to calculate a solution to the equation of radiative transfer.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation is distinct from the two-stream approximation.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The two-stream approximation assumes that the intensity is constant with angle in the upward hemisphere, with a different constant value in the downward hemisphere.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] $I_{\nu }(\mu ,z)=a(z)+\mu b(z)$ where z is the normal direction to the slab-like medium.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Note that expressing angular integrals in terms of $\mu$ simplifies things because $d\mu =-\sin \theta \,d\theta$ appears in the Jacobian of integrals in spherical coordinates.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation can be used to obtain the spectral radiance in a "plane-parallel" medium (one in which properties only vary in the perpendicular direction) with isotropic frequency-independent scattering.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Thus the Eddington approximation is equivalent to setting ${\textstyle K_{\nu }={\frac {1}{3}}J_{\nu }}$ .
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Higher order versions of the Eddington approximation also exist, and consist of more complicated linear relations of the intensity moments.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] This extra equation can be used as a closure relation for the truncated system of moments.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] Note that the first two moments have simple physical meanings. $J_{\nu }$ is the isotropic intensity at a point, and $H_{\nu }$ is the flux through that point in the z direction.
[src:climate-modeling/radiative-transfer] This equation shows how the effective optical depth in scattering-dominated systems may be significantly different from that given by the scattering opacity if the absorptive opacity is small.
